The article discusses the Armenian genocide, which began on April 24, 1915, when Armenian intellectuals and community leaders were arrested by Ottoman authorities in Constantinople. It reflects on the one and a half million Armenians who were deported, massacred, or marched to their deaths, and emphasizes the need to remain vigilant against hate and to speak out against atrocities. The article also highlights the resilience of the Armenian people and their contributions to the United States. It concludes by stating that the American people continue to honor all Armenians who perished in the genocide, even 107 years later.